The '''Estates of Navarre''' ''(French: États de Navarre, États généraux de Navarre, Cortes de Navarre)''<ref name="Orpustan (n.d.), p. 9">Orpustan (n.d.), p. 9 [http://tipirena.net/Tipirena_-_Site_officiel_de_Jean-Baptiste_ORPUSTAN/VI._Varia_files/La%20Basse.pdf (in French)]</ref> were created in 1317 under [[Philip V of France|Philip II]]. The '''Estates of [[Lower Navarre]]''' ''(French: États de Basse-Navarre,<ref name="Daranatz (1923), Part 1">Daranatz (1923), Part 1)]</ref> Cortes de la Basse-Navarre)''<ref name="Orpustan (n.d.), p. 9" /> were first called into session on 28 August 1523<ref name="Orpustan (n.d.), p. 9" /><ref name="Daranatz (1923), Part 1" /><ref name="Esarte Muniain (2001), p. 667">Esarte Muniain (2001), p. 667</ref><ref name="AD64, E 564">AD64, E 564 [http://earchives.le64.fr/ead.html?id=FRAD064003_IR0006&c=FRAD064003_IR0006_de-566&qid=eas1461344707935 (in French]</ref> by [[Henry II of Navarre|Henry II]] after [[Spanish conquest of Iberian Navarre|the definitive loss]] of [[Upper Navarre]],<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 608">Lafourcade (2003), p. 608 [http://www.euskomedia.org/PDFAnlt/riev/48/48589619.pdf (in French)]</ref>
It was created in the model of the Estates General that already existed in the Court of [[Pamplona#A fortress-city|Pamplona]], the [[Estates General (France)|Estates General of France]], and in [[Estates of Béarn|Béarn]] and other provinces.<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 608" /> The last meeting of the Estates of [[Lower Navarre]] was on 15 June 1789.
== Composition ==
The '''Estates of [[Lower Navarre]]''' was composed of deputies from the three [[Estates of the realm#Kingdom of France|Estates]]: the First Estate ([[clergy]]), the Second Estate ([[French nobility|nobility]]) and the Third Estate ([[commoners]]), each deputy having one vote.<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 608" />
* For the First Estate, the [[regular clergy]], the [[Bishop of Bayonne]], the [[Bishop of Dax]], the [[Deanery|Dean]] of [[Saint-Jean-Pied-de-Port]] and the [[Prior]]s of [[Saint-Palais, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Saint-Palais]], [[Larceveau-Arros-Cibits|Utziate]] and [[Ostabat-Asme|Harambels]], six persons in all. The bishops rarely appeared. The [[Bishop of Bayonne]] was represented by the [[Archdeacon]] of ''[[Ostabarret|Pay de Cize]]'', who was the [[parish]] [[priest]] of [[Saint-Jean-Pied-de-Port]], and the [[Bishop of Dax]] by the [[Archdeacon]] of ''[[Ostabarret|Pays de Mixe]]'' and the ''[[Ostabarret|Pays d'Ostabarret]]'', who was the [[parish]] [[priest]] of [[Saint-Palais, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Saint-Palais]];<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 608" /> * For the Second Estate, the [[French nobility|nobility]], was composed of all of the owners of noble properties in [[Lower Navarre]], of which the number varied in the [[early modern period]] between 103 and 153, depending on the author. The relative number demonstrates the importance of the nobility in the small [[Lower Navarre|Kingdom of Lower Navarre]];<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 608" /> * For the Third Estate, the [[commoners]], the representation was quite complex due to the decentralized administrative structure of the country, composed of seven ''"lands"'' or valleys and five cities. Two of them, the ''[[Ostabarret|Pays de Mixe]]'' and the combined trilogy of [[Armendarits]]-[[Iholdy]]-[[Irissarry]] designated three representatives; the others, the ''[[Ostabarret|Pay de Cize]]'', the ''[[:fr:Arberoue (pays)|Pays d’Arberoue]]'', the ''[[Ostabarret|Pays d'Ostabarret]]'' and the ''[[:fr:Baïgorry-Ossès|Ossès]]'' and ''[[Vallée des Aldudes|Baïgorry]] Valleys'' nominated two; the five cities of [[La Bastide-Clairence]], [[Garris, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Garris]], [[Saint-Palais, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Saint-Palais]], [[Larceveau-Arros-Cibits|Larceveau]] and [[Saint-Jean-Pied-de-Port]] each designated two. The representatives of the Third Estate were all attorneys, 26 in total for the Estates of Navarre.<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 609">Lafourcade (2003), p. 609 [http://www.euskomedia.org/PDFAnlt/riev/48/48589619.pdf (in French)]</ref>
== Operation == The Estates of Navarre guaranteed that high-ranking officials of the Royal Council observed the requirements. On several occasions, the Estates filed complaints regarding the appointment of Royal Council and Chancery members. One complaint referred to the appointment of royal councillors and attorneys with no command of [[Basque language|Basque]].<ref name="Orbea, J.M./Adot, A. (2014), p. 26">Orbea, J.M./Adot, A. (2014), p. 26</ref>
A first breach of the regulations and its related grievance referred to the ''affaire Jean de Laforcade'' in 1590, following his appointment as attorney general. He hailed from [[County of Foix|Foix]], so his appointment was appealed for failing to meet the birthplace and Basque language requirements. The General Courts (Estates) urged the king to remove him from office.<ref name="Orbea, J.M./Adot, A. (2014), p. 26" /><ref>"(...) per no estar lo dict de la Forcade natural deu present reaume ni haver la inteligencia deu lengoadge basco, bulgar [customary] en aquel"</ref>
The Estates guaranteed up to 1624 that the language standards remained in place. The [[Parliament of Navarre and Béarn|Parliament of Navarre]] with a seat in [[Pau, Pyrénées-Atlantiques|Pau]] was then established out of a merger of the [[Chancery of Navarre|Chancery]] and [[Council of Navarre]] with the sovereign [[Council of Béarn]]; they ceased to exist. The new Parliament was then composed of a chief chairman, designated by the King, seven presiding deputies, two knights of honour, 46 councillors, two solicitors, and a general attorney.<ref name="Orbea, J.M./Adot, A. (2014), p. 26" />
However, in the run-up to the 1624 dissolution of the Royal Council under Louis II ([[Louis XIII of France]]), a reform almost discarded the Basque language requirement citing certain edicts decreed by Henry III ([[Henry IV of France]]) which made any person of his choosing eligible for appointment to an office, "without difference of birth or religion", so that the preceptive [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]]se origin was never again mandatory either. The Three Estates accepted the new ruling, while at the same time demanding that Basque be mandatory for the councillors, except for one.<ref name="Orbea, J.M./Adot, A. (2014), p. 28">Orbea, J.M./Adot, A. (2014), p. 28</ref><ref>The councillors had to be "versez en la langue basque, toutesfois y pourra avoir un conseiller ne sachant la dite langue"</ref>
Despite the centralizing drive of the French crown, the Estates still kept significant legislating powers until 1748, when a decree by [[Louis XV of France]] stripped them off.<ref name="Lafourcade (2003), p. 616">Lafourcade (2003), p. 616</ref> The archives of the ''Estates of Navarre'' for the period 1317–1789 are held at the Archives Départementales des Pyrénées-Atlantiques.<ref name="AD64, États de Navarre">AD64, États de Navarre</ref>
==See also== *[[Viscounty of Béarn]] *[[Juntas Generales]] *[[Parliament of Navarre]] *[[History of the Basques#Modern Period|History of the Basques]]
