'''Marshall Howard Saville''' (1867–1935) was an [[United States|American]] [[archaeologist]], born in [[Rockport, Massachusetts]]. He studied [[anthropology]] at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] (1889–94), engaged in field work under [[Frederic Ward Putnam|F. W. Putnam]], and made important discoveries among the [[Mound builder (people)|mound builders]] in southern [[Ohio]]. After 1903 he was professor of American archæology at [[Columbia University]]. He also became director of an important private museum in New York, the [[Museum of the American Indian]] ([[Heye Foundation]]). Saville conducted many explorations to various places such as [[Yucatan]], Honduras, Mexico, Ecuador and Colombia.
Saville was a founding member of [[the Explorers Club]], an organization formally established in 1905 and dedicated to promoting exploration and scientific investigation in the field.<ref>{{cite web |year=2002 |title=About the Club: A Gathering Place |url=http://www.explorers.org/about/history/gatheringplace.php |work=The Explorers Club: Promoting Exploration and Field Sciences Since 1904 |publisher=[[Explorers Club]] |accessdate=2008-03-31 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080719133757/http://www.explorers.org/about/history/gatheringplace.php <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-07-19}}</ref>
